[{"id":"VR788683","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows an electron at rest next to an electric field vector E, which points vertically upward.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR788683.g03.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">An electron is initially at rest in a uniform electric field <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"vector E\"><math alttext=\"vector E\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>E</mi><mo>â†’</mo></mover></math></span></span> that points upward, as shown in the figure. After the electron starts moving in the field, what happens to the electric potential energy <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub e f, end sub\"><math alttext=\"U sub e f, end sub\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mtext>e-f</mtext></msub></math></span></span> of the electron-field system? What evidence or reasoning best supports the claim? Gravitational forces can be considered to be negligible.</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR788683_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub e f, end sub\"><math alttext=\"U sub e f, end sub\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mtext>e-f</mtext></msub></math></span></span> increases. The electron moves in the opposite direction that a positive charge would move.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub e f, end sub\"><math alttext=\"U sub e f, end sub\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mtext>e-f</mtext></msub></math></span></span> increases. The electron is accelerated by the field and has an increasing kinetic energy.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub e f, end sub\"><math alttext=\"U sub e f, end sub\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mtext>e-f</mtext></msub></math></span></span> decreases. The electron moves upward.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub e f, end sub\"><math alttext=\"U sub e f, end sub\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mtext>e-f</mtext></msub></math></span></span> decreases. The speed of the electron increases due to the field and the electron has an increasing kinetic energy.</p>"],"answer":3}]